Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Long memory  - motivation", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.406269143060752*^9, 3.406269147568752*^9}, {
   3.530599059624044*^9, 3.530599065584362*^9}, {3.530691073690981*^9, 
   3.530691075674041*^9}, {3.53069147302001*^9, 3.530691474871354*^9}, {
   3.530693029400872*^9, 3.5306930616095943`*^9}, {3.530794625264617*^9, 
   3.530794629791909*^9}, 3.623998439273554*^9, {3.624909357014391*^9, 
   3.62490936629243*^9}, {3.6249094474592047`*^9, 3.6249094508498917`*^9}, {
   3.8574668228634357`*^9, 
   3.857466835638348*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9b4db01a-271b-4ed6-8446-\
a3efb0626382"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Several disciplines came to realizations that naturally occurring phenomena \
(river flow, atmospheric patterns, telecommunications, economics, etc) \
exhibit correlations that do not decay at a sufficiently fast rate.\n\nIt is \
difficult to distinguish between I(1) and I(0). Thus, knife-edge distinction \
between I(0) and I(1) processes can be far too restrictive.\n\nVolatility of \
asset prices can be successfully approximated by long memory models. \n\n\
Significant correlations in observations are separated by great periods of \
time.\n\nOccurrence of jumps\n\nLong memory time series require different \
approaches to modeling than the short memory time series.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Application to fin. markets: Ding, Zhuanxin, Clive WJ Granger, and \
Robert F. Engle. \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]A long memory property of stock \
market returns and a new model.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] Journal of empirical \
finance 1.1 (1993): 83-106.",
  FontSize->12],
 "\n\n",
 StyleBox["Example:", "Subsection"],
 "\nprediction of long memory process: Red line is prediction based on AR(3) \
and the yellow one is appropriate long memory process.\n  "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.475525979705353*^9, 3.475525999449602*^9}, {
   3.475526413767523*^9, 3.475526417765077*^9}, {3.475526448467842*^9, 
